A single, derivative-free identity that puts **all of \(\rho\)** on one side and **only the metric (via its volume element) on the other** is the pull-back relation for the *mass form*:

\[
\boxed{\;
\Phi_t^{\!*}\!\bigl(\,\rho_t\,dV_{g_t}\bigr)
\;=\;
\rho_0\,dV_{g_0}\;}
\tag{1}
\]

* \(dV_{g_t}(y)=\sqrt{\det g_t(y)}\,dy\) is the Riemannian volume form of the deterministic metric \(g_t=\Phi_t^{\!*}g_0\).
* \(\Phi_t^{\!*}\) denotes pathwise pull-back by the stochastic flow \(\Phi_t\).

---

### Coordinate version  

Set \(y=\Phi_t(x)\).  Because \(J_t(x):=\det D_x\Phi_t(x)=\sqrt{\det g_t(y)/\det g_0(x)}\),

\[
\boxed{\;
\rho_t\!\bigl(\Phi_t(x)\bigr)
=
\frac{\rho_0(x)\,\sqrt{\det g_0(x)}}{\sqrt{\det g_t\!\bigl(\Phi_t(x)\bigr)}}\;}
\tag{2}
\]

which can be averaged over noise to obtain the physical density

\[
\boxed{\;
\rho_t(y)\sqrt{\det g_t(y)}
=
\mathbb E\!\Bigl[\,\rho_0\!\bigl(\Phi_{-t}(y)\bigr)\sqrt{\det g_0\!\bigl(\Phi_{-t}(y)\bigr)}\,\Bigr].}
\tag{3}
\]

Equations (1)–(3) make the dependence explicit: the metric enters only through its determinant (the Jacobian), while every stochastic effect sits inside the expectation over the random pre-image \(\Phi_{-t}(y)\).

\[
\boxed{\;\rho_t(y)=\mathbb{E}_{W(\cdot)}^{\;\sigma^2=2D}\Bigl[\rho_0\bigl(\Phi_{-t}(y;\sqrt{2D}\,W)\bigr)\,J_t^{-1}\bigl(\Phi_{-t}(y;\sqrt{2D}\,W)\bigr)\Bigr]\;}
\]
